An ambitious £1.1m overhaul of London's transport infrastructure will see dozens of underground and bus stations converted into tourist attractions, luxury apartments and new homes.

The ten-year project will see 50 sites owned by Transport for London turned into profit-generating businesses, as they become home to supermarkets, restaurants and even 'click and collect' depots for online retailers. 

The move, which will involve some 10million sq ft of land, will mean the organisation receives an regular income from its huge property portfolio, said to be one of the largest and most valuable in the capital.

